0.user_question: Dana can run at a rate of speed four times faster than she can walk, but she can skip at a rate of speed that is half as fast as she can run. If she can skip at 3 miles per hour, how many miles can she travel in six hours if she spends one-third of the time running and two-thirds of the time walking?

direct_answer.text: Let's think step by step. Dana skips at a speed of 3 mph which means she runs at twice this speed (since it’s doubled). Therefore, she runs at 3*2=6mph and walks at 6/4=1.5mph because running speed is four times higher compared to walking speed.   If she spent only third of her journey while running we get distance traveled during running equals : Speed×Time; here speed when running would equal 6miles per hr ×(6hrours÷3)=12 miles . Similarly , if she walked two-thirds of her trip, distance covered whilst walking would equal:Speed×Time; Here speed when walking = 1.5milesperhour ; Time Spent Walking = 6hours∗2⁄3=4 hrs.; Distance Covered While Wandering = Speed×time = 1.5x4=6 miles    Total Miles Traveled During Six Hour Period Would Equal Running Mileage+Walking Mileage=Total Trip Length That Is Combined Sum Of Two Parts Which Are Both Less Than or Equal To One
